Here's someone who's just fixing my kitchen floor. And now I'm pretending to have another job and working from home while I'm sitting on Too Hot to Handle.
If I could just damn well open the file. (Damn One Drive.)
*Voice of a Hacker* I'm in.
And that's exactly when it starts drilling super loudly. Yay!
It feels uncomfortably passive-aggressive to crank my air purifier to its maximum, but I can smell the wood dust, so it would even be completely okay, even if he wasn't a mask opponent. And do I really need to protect myself?
I would really like to go back to bed, but I can't until he leaves.
At least I finally finished revising Chapter 4!
Chapter five is long, but so damn terrifying. Oh yeah, that's the good stuff!
I'm doing search and replace for … ➡️ ellipsis symbol, and there are 54 of them in this chapter 😅
But no, I stand by my statement. Natural language is usually fragmented, especially when one becomes emotional.
The craftsman is now using the vacuum cleaner. Hopefully, that means he'll be finished soon.
He went out to cut something (at least that's how it sounded). I secretly checked once to see how far he was. There's still a lot to do :(
Still 7 pages in chapter 5. It's still my favorite chapter and it's quite neat – mainly changes to the font and very small corrections in direct speech, and I need to formulate everything a bit more compactly. But I really could use a break and a cup of tea now, but the guy is still in my kitchen.
Now he's just started vacuuming again. Hopefully, that's a good sign.
The kitchen type is gone!
He told me that he had made a cost estimate for the entire floor, but the landlords were stingy and only paid for the part next to the door that is no longer in working order. It feels much better now.
The house is being ventilated, and my air purifier is running in the kitchen while I'm drinking tea in the garden!
